      {
        "id": 4352876,
        "name": "Mich@el Ch@ng",
        "username": "MChang",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/mchang/{size}/352156_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-04-24T20:16:14.019Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-Monopole_Cru\" data-username=\"J.Vizuete\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"321299\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/j.vizuete/48/2784_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> J.Vizuete:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I have a bottle of 17 and would be eager to hear from anyone with experience with this vineyard. Although I generally find 2017 to be a charming and approachable vintage, Roumier seems to need more time than just about anybody else in burgundy. A 17 MSD Bussiere was tight and unyielding last July, so I wasn\u2019t planning on opening mine any time soon. To say nothing of more recent releases\u2026</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I\u2019ve found recent Roumier to be pretty accessible, bussiere is actually one of the ones that needs the most time, even more so then the bonnes mares.</p>",
